  "texts": [
    "It is represented by the setO = {α, β, γ},where α denotes a policy of zero immigration and strictness toward immigrants, while β and γ correspond to progressively more open policies.The political space of Gallopolis is therefore defined as the product setA = E × S × O.Within this space, five political parties constitute the principal political forces, each characterized by a set of desirable states:LEFT = {2, 3} × {l} × {γ}, SOCD = {2} × {l, n} × {β, γ}, CONS = {1, 2} × {n, c} × {α, β}, LIBER = {1} × {l} × {α, β, γ} ∪ {1} × {n} × {β, γ} RIGHT = {1, 2} × {c} × {α}.• The nerve of Gallopolis is the following simplicial complex represented by its geometric realization.• LEFT • SOCD • CONS • LIBER • RIGHT (2,ℓ,γ) (2,n,β) ( 1, n, β) ( 1, c, α), ( 2, c, α)(5)The nerve is a simplicial complex of dimension 1.",
    "In the figure every simplex of dimension 1 is affected by the states that are in the intersection of its vertices.• The parting function of Gallopolis π ≡ π a can be partially read on graphic (5), precisely:-on the states that connect two vertices we have:π(2, l, γ) = {LEFT, SOCD}, π(2, n, β) = {SOCD, CONS}, etc.-On the rest of the states the parting function is as follows:π(3, l, γ) = {LEFT}, π(1, l, α) = π(1, l, β) = π(1, l, γ) = π(1, n, γ) = {LIBER}, π(2, n, γ) = π(2, l, β) = {SOCD}, π(1, c, β) = π(1, n, α) = π(2, n, α) = π(2, c, β) = {CONS}.-the parting function takes the value ∅ on the states, that do not belong to any party, for instance (1, c, γ), (3, l, α), (3, l, β), (3, n, α),...• The Knit of Gallopolis, κ a, is the image of the parting function π a.",
    "It has as maximal elements precisely the simplexes of dimension 1 of the nerve, the other elements being ∅, {LEFT}, {LIBER}, {SOCD}, {CONS}.",
    "Therefore the Knit of Gallopolis (including the empty set) is a complex of cardinality 9.",
    "The only \"coalition\" that is present in the nerve but absent from the Knit is {RIGHT}.Note that, in this model of the polity, every party except RIGHT can be identified by characteristic principles."
  ],
